  "prompt": "What are the best books of body language?",
  "response": "There are several highly regarded books on body language that offer insights into nonverbal communication. Here are some of the best-known ones:\n\n1. **\"The Definitive Book of Body Language\" by Allan and Barbara Pease**  \n   This book is a comprehensive guide on understanding and interpreting body language. It covers everything from facial expressions to gestures and postures.\n\n2. **\"What Every BODY is Saying: An Ex-FBI Agent\u2019s Guide to Speed-Reading People\" by Joe Navarro**  \n   Joe Navarro, a former FBI agent, provides practical advice on interpreting nonverbal cues and understanding what people are communicating without words.\n\n3. **\"Body Language\" by Julius Fast**  \n   One of the earlier works on the subject, this book introduces readers to the basics of body language and its implications in everyday interactions.\n\n4. **\"The Like Switch: An Ex-FBI Agent's Guide to Influencing, Attracting, and Winning People Over\" by Jack Schafer and Marvin Karlins**  \n   This book offers insights into using body language effectively to improve relationships and influence others.\n\n5. **\"Emotions Revealed: Recognizing Faces and Feelings to Improve Communication and Emotional Life\" by Paul Ekman**  \n   Paul Ekman, a leading psychologist in the study of emotions and facial expressions, provides valuable insights into how facial expressions reveal emotions.\n\n6. **\"You Say More Than You Think: Use the New Body Language to Get What You Want!\" by Janine Driver**  \n   Janine Driver offers a fresh perspective on how to use body language to communicate more effectively and achieve personal and professional goals.\n\n7. **\"Louder than Words: Take Your Career from Average to Exceptional with the Hidden Power of Nonverbal Intelligence\" by Joe Navarro**  \n   Another book by Joe Navarro, it delves into using body language to enhance professional success.\n\n8. **\"Spy the Lie: Former CIA Officers Teach You How to Detect Deception\" by Philip Houston, Michael Floyd, and Susan Carnicero**  \n   While more focused on detecting deception, this book includes tips on identifying signs of dishonesty through body language.\n\nThese books provide valuable insights into nonverbal communication, offering strategies for reading others more accurately and improving your own body language.",
